ent/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-374 alignleft\" alt=\"DSC01134 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01134-Custom.jpg\" width=\"240\" height=\"320\" /></a>\r\n</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-375\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" /></a></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                                                                                                                                                                     Gauri</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">                              Tulsi</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Tulsi was born November 2003 and her sister Gauri was born April 2005.  Both are living at the Sahar Orphanage.  They are in 3rd and 2nd standard respectively.  Their mother died in a road accident.  Their father had no job and was homeless so he brought the girls to the orphanage.   He hopes to collect them after they complete school through the 7th standard at Sahar,  by which time he hopes his personal situation will have improved.</p>','Tulsi & Gauri Shetty','','inherit','open','open','','162-revision-v1','','','2014-03-13 13:18:09','2014-03-13 13:18:09','',162,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/162-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(405,1,'2014-03-14 01:07:37','2014-03-14 01:07:37','This is a blog of a visit to the HMBT orphanages in December, 2009 written by a 13 year old girl and her father.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Sunday, November 22, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning our trip to India</strong>\r\n\r\nWe\'re planning our trip to India. We are planning to volunteer at the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity orphanage, in the Sahar Slum of Mumbai, where we will be trying to teach the kids there English. We are learning a little bit of Hindi before we go so it will be easier to get to know the people at the orphanage. There will be thirty kids there ages running from 4 to 12.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 9, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\nWe are already starting to get some donations for the Orphanages. This is really exciting we are looking forward to actually meeting the orphans.\r\n<div>\r\n<div>[sectiontitle]Sunday, December 13, 2009[/sectiontitle]</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary1.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary1\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary1-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOn our first day at the Sahar Orphanage we were welcomed very warmly. The kids knew that we were coming and happy to finally see us. We’ve gone to two of the orphanages so far. At the first one we helped the kids a little with their English writing letters and numbers. At the big orphanage my dad (who is a doctor) checked over the kids and helped diagnose their conditions. I think the kids have a lot of responsibility and they are all mothering each other because they are all like a big family. The sisters devoted their whole lives to help these children and they are doing a really good j0b. It seems like the community the big orphanage is in is really nice, they contribute food on holidays and Sundays. The slums in real life are exactly what they look like in “Slumdog Millionaire”. It’s sad looking at the kids running through the traffic begging for food and money…\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Monday, December 14, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary2\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-372c-849e-1281-fb95cd743eac\">The Sisters running the Sahar Slum Orphanage also run another orphanage at Vasai. There are 200 kids here, boys and girls, aged from 5 to 14. This orphanage is in a country setting.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday when we were at the Vasai orphanage we saw a girl with polio. Her aged face was the only reason we could tell she was older than 11. She was all curled up and her back was very deformed. She got polio when she was really young and she survived. Her parents couldn’t deal with a crippled child so they abandoned her to the orphanage. The nuns don’t have enough money to buy her a wheelchair or time to do physical therapy. We are using some of the money we collected from donations to get a wheelchair for her so she doesn’t have to ever drag herself around with only her arms again.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary3\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2eb0e328-372f-7b9f-d3da-cb51a7367ade\">Though the traffic is CRAZY here, i think it is safe because everybody is watching out for themselves and looking more at their surroundings. In America there are so many rules that if somebody breaks one, people aren’t prepared and there is panic and confusion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary4\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">People in India seem very casual and easy going. We were walking through the slums to get to the orphanage and we came across a few boys playing outside with a top. They said “hi” and I stopped to watch them and take their picture. They didn’t speak English but they all lined up for me to take a photo. It was surprising that people living in such poverty could be so free and friendly.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even the dogs seem laid back; they never bark or chase you.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary5\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3730-d48f-f750-b23c8486e647\">The slums are very smelly and dirty. There are open sewers and piles of garbage throughout the slum village. The filth is scattered around houses and the marketplace.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And yet there is still beauty in the slums…</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary6.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary6\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary6-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary7\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3731-87c0-c81e-8d26bdc27188\">We have been visiting the Sahar slum orphanage that is run by sisters Eliza and Paulette of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Today we went to the orphanage just expecting the thirty orphans but we found out that the orphanage is also the site of a low cost school for the slums. There were 500 kids aged 3-14 packed into classrooms with a collective space similar to a three bedroom apartment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some kids start school late so there are a few older kids in lower standards (grades). For example there is a girl in this slum school who was born and raised in a small village and her family just moved to the slum area to get jobs in the city. They then started sending her to the school so now she is in the second standard even though she’s already 13 years old.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary8\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary9\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 16, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary10\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe were waiting outside the Sahar Orphanage and I was sketching out possible pictures for the kids to learn how to draw. A group of 4th standard slum kids just getting out of school walked by in their uniforms. They stopped to look at my pictures and my dad sat them all down around me and handed out sheets of paper. A boy and a small girl got their pencils out and I taught them how to draw a dinosaur. It was a happy experience changing this group of slum kid’s day from just average to great. They really like getting one on one attention and it feels really good to help these kids.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary11.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary11\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary11-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn the same day we did a friendship bracelet project with the orphans. Some of the kids caught on really fast and didn’t need any help; they helped some of the younger kids who didn’t understand how to make the bracelets.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary12\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTalking with Sister Eliza, we learned more about the history of the orpahange. An old couple lived in a shack, in the Sahar Village slums, just behind the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. The husband worked pumping water from the nearby well. He was somehow murdered on the Flight Kitchen’s property and his body was thrown in a well. The Kitchen compensated the wife by giving her property on which she then built a small slum house. When she died she left the house and property to the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Eventually this property was expanded to become what is now the Sahar Village school and orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary13\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3734-8fa5-fcd9-014bbaa5d876\">Sister Eliza is about 50 years old but she looks like and has the energy of a much younger person. She came from Goa, India. When she was in college in Mumbai she studied Social Work in the slums and that is how she met Sister Paulette. Together they lived in the slums and were homeless until they were left a small home for their work.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza is very lively but at the same time very strict with the orphans. All the kids respect her. She is always smiling and seems very happy about her work. She stays busy all day long. In the morning she teaches 4th standard at the orphanage/school. In the afternoon she goes and teaches at a private school to earn money for the orphanage. Every Saturday night she leaves for Vasai to join Sister Paulette for the weekend. Between teaching, traveling back and forth between her three orphanages, and running the orphanages, she’s left with no time to herself.</p>\r\nSister Paulette worked with Mother Teresa for about twenty years until she became very sick and was sent to a hospital in Mumbai. She was paralyzed and the doctor told her she was going to be bedridden for life. Sister Paulette told us that Mother Mary appeared to her and told her to get up and go back to help people. Somehow she had a miraculous recovery and started working in the Sahar Village Slum. Today she spends most of her time at the Vasai Orphanage helping the 200 kids there. Sister Paulette told us that she believes in “fighting poverty by education”. She says: “Giving food helps for a day or two but educating saves an entire life.”\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary14\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAma is the caretaker of the Sahar Orphanage, she monitors the kids and she is like their mother. She gave up her own home and all personal belongings to come and live at the orphanage. She bathes the kids and feeds them and dresses them. She is always there for them and most of the village knows her. Her being there takes a lot of the burden off Sister Eliza and frees her up to be able to go to the other orphanages. Ama can be very strict at times, and she really knows how to keep the kids in order. They are her whole life and she loves them like they are her own children.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary15\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe daily schedule for the Sahar Orphanage children starts in the morning with Ama bathing them and then feeding them. For breakfast they get one banana, one glass of milk, bread, butter, and jam. The bread, butter, and jam are donated by the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. Sister Eliza pays three Rupees for each kid to have an egg every morning. After breakfast they go to their classrooms until 1:00 p.m. Ama then feeds them a lunch of dhal, rice, and water. After they eat, they get rest and play time. A tutor comes in the afternoon and works with them. After this they get a snack and have free time until Ama is ready to feed them dinner. Dinner consists of a glass of water, rice, and leftovers from lunch and breakfast.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary16\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary17.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary17\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary17-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-6283-c35c-bd6907b38d00\">In Mumbai kids are usually orphaned because either the parents are in jail, they’ve died, or the fathers left the mothers. Often the story is that one or both of the parents have died of AIDS. In cases where the father has left the mother, the mother is often left homeless or unable to cope with a full time job and care for a child.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once, we were walking home from a restaurant and we passed a frail middle aged woman holding a baby. She looked really sad. She was so desperate that she wasn’t begging for money, she was just standing in the middle of a street saying “khana” (food) to all passers. When we saw her, we gave her a bag of food that we got from the restaurant and she said: “God bless you.” Seeing people like that makes you want to give them everything you have because you know that they need it a lot more than you do.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary18\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-a7ee-8ff2-f70c3021eef4\">Poverty in India is EVERYWHERE. You could be inside the property of a five star, top line, hotel but as soon as you walk outside you would see a family bundled up on a few scraps of blankets. Or a mother trying to bathe her children in water from a pipe leak.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary19\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-fb97-ecd7-dd6ff730c291\">In America poor people on the streets are usually not literally “on the streets.” There are soup kitchens and food lines they can go to, there are people who set up organizations to shelter the homeless for a night or two.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And if a homeless person wanted to get off the streets, he/she probably could. In India, we did not see soup kitchens or “shelter for the poor” organizations; people are pretty much on their own. There are whole families living under a lean-to they’ve set up with scraps of blankets and wood. We saw a family</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3737-1e3a-f7ca-68ab726c3003\">bathing in water from a sewage leak right on a busy traffic road, and cooking in a tin can over a small fire. These families don’t have enough money to send their kids to school, and they’re too busy trying to get food to even think about education.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Thursday, December 17, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-92 alignnone\" alt=\"diary20\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1e-85b8-0f6e-6c08da776bc0\">At the Vasai Orphanage we saw that almost every kid had a skin infection on their legs and arms and other parts of the body. My dad sent pictures to an infection specialist at the University of Michigan and he wrote back with helpful advice to have one child with the infection tested at a local hospital.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday we took an orphan to Holy Spirit Hospital in Mumbai hoping to get some tests done. The hospitals in India are very different from American hospitals. There was a huge line of about forty people all waiting to get their papers and to get checked by just one doctor. When we finally got to see the doctor, he told us what we already thought- the orphan had scabies and bacteria infections of the skin. He did not allow any tests to be done.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dad became friends with a pharmacist nearby where we were staying. When the pharmacist heard what we were doing he said that he would give us medicine at the best price he could. We purchased enough medicine to treat all the orphans at both Vasai and Sahar.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-93\" alt=\"diary21\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1f-4aba-c7c3-ce380f6890fd\">We spent a lot of time making charts of which children should take what doses of each medicine. On the last day, my dad weighed all the kids at the Sahar orphanage to make it easier for Sister Eliza to distribute the medication.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary22.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-94\" alt=\"diary22\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary22-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1f-b142-efc1-cebbe252de44\">At Vasai all the orphans and caretakers bathe with water from a very shallow well. The well is covered by a wire dome. Sister Eliza told us that the kids sometimes misbehaved and threw toothbrushes and spit in the well. Sometimes they even urinated in the well. The kids don\'t have parents to discipline them and Sisters Eliza and Paulette are doing the best they can. The well is also located a few feet away from the pit toilets and we are worried that when it rains there is cross-contamination.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We talked to the Sisters about our concerns with the current water situation and they said that they were uncomfortable with it also. They have paid a man to go down and clean out the well and they put a solid cover over the well. They also built a locked fence around the well so no kids can get through.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this is a good short term solution to the water problem, in monsoon season, there is going to be a lot of cross contamination and the water will become filthy again. . They have been thinking about it for a while and they both thought that the best idea would be to get a solar powered water boiler installed. Getting and installing this boiler will cost 150,000 rupees (the equivalent of a little over 3,000 U.S. dollars). Our short term goal is to raise enough money to buy this boiler for the orphanage.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-2889-abfd-6562625193b9\">Today is our last day in Mumbai. We are taking a train to Vadodara to visit my dad\'s family. We are very glad to have had the chance to work at these orphanages.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At times working at the orphanages was REALLY frustrating. The Orphans would start fighting for attention while we were talking to other kids and grabbing things from other kid’s hands. But at the end of every day at the orphanage, when they were all waving bye to us and walking us to the door shouting “good-bye Dee-Dee” (goodbye big sister) I felt good because I knew that the orphans were really happy. Seeing new people who wanted to help them was a big treat for them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-95\" alt=\"diary23\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-7c6d-80ed-f258b5054a58\">I was glad that I wasn’t just out seeing the Taj-ma-hal or some other attraction; instead, I was finally doing something that helped someone else.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Writing this blog has been hard work because we are always doing it at the end of the day when we are exhausted and jet-lagged. I just want to go to sleep but my dad drags me down to the hotel lobby and asks to use the manager’s computer for a while. We go through all the pictures from the day, select the few we actually want to keep, and match them with things that had happened that day.\r\n\r\nAfter volunteering only for one week I have become amazed that the Sisters have devoted their whole lives to doing this work. It’s REALLY HARD. They have given up everything in their lives to help the orphans and their whole lives revolve around them. The only reason they do ANYTHING is for the orphans. They are so self-less and devoted, and not many people are like them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-96\" alt=\"diary24\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this blog is for memories and for showing others how different lives are in the slums in India, it is also to raise money. The Sisters have a wish-list of things they can’t afford. The solar-water boiler for the Vasai orphanage is something we’ve seen that they really need and there is NO way that they are going to get this without donors. Our goal is to raise $3500 for this project. If you are reading this please consider making a donation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary25.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-72\" alt=\"diary25\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary25-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-03-14 01:07:37','2014-03-14 01:07:37','',9,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(407,1,'2014-03-14 01:26:05','2014-03-14 01:26:05','','learning_1000x400','','inherit','open','open','','learning_1000x400','','','2014-03-14 01:26:05','2014-03-14 01:26:05','',0,'http://handmaids-local/wp-content/uploads/learning_1000x400.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(412,1,'2014-03-15 15:56:20','2014-03-15 15:56:20','Thank you for contacting Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. We appreciate your interest in our organization.','Thank You','','publish','open','open','','thank-you','','','2014-03-15 15:56:20','2014-03-15 15:56:20','',123,'http://handmaids-local/?page_id=412',-1,'page','',0),(413,1,'2014-03-15 15:56:20','2014-03-15 15:56:20','Thank you for contacting Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. We appreciate your interest in our organization.','Thank You','','inherit','open','open','','412-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 15:56:20','2014-03-15 15:56:20','',412,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/412-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(429,1,'2014-03-16 19:53:54','2014-03-16 19:53:54','This is a blog of a visit to the HMBT orphanages in December, 2009 written by a 13 year old girl and her father.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Sunday, November 22, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\n<strong>Planning our trip to India</strong>\r\n\r\nWe\'re planning our trip to India. We are planning to volunteer at the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity orphanage, in the Sahar Slum of Mumbai, where we will be trying to teach the kids there English. We are learning a little bit of Hindi before we go so it will be easier to get to know the people at the orphanage. There will be thirty kids there ages running from 4 to 12.\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 9, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n\r\nWe are already starting to get some donations for the Orphanages. This is really exciting we are looking forward to actually meeting the orphans.\r\n<div>\r\n<div>[sectiontitle]Sunday, December 13, 2009[/sectiontitle]</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary1.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary1\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary1-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\nOn our first day at the Sahar Orphanage we were welcomed very warmly. The kids knew that we were coming and happy to finally see us. We’ve gone to two of the orphanages so far. At the first one we helped the kids a little with their English writing letters and numbers. At the big orphanage my dad (who is a doctor) checked over the kids and helped diagnose their conditions. I think the kids have a lot of responsibility and they are all mothering each other because they are all like a big family. The sisters devoted their whole lives to help these children and they are doing a really good j0b. It seems like the community the big orphanage is in is really nice, they contribute food on holidays and Sundays. The slums in real life are exactly what they look like in “Slumdog Millionaire”. It’s sad looking at the kids running through the traffic begging for food and money…\r\n\r\n[sectiontitle]Monday, December 14, 2009[/sectiontitle]\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary2\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary2-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-372c-849e-1281-fb95cd743eac\">The Sisters running the Sahar Slum Orphanage also run another orphanage at Vasai. There are 200 kids here, boys and girls, aged from 5 to 14. This orphanage is in a country setting.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday when we were at the Vasai orphanage we saw a girl with polio. Her aged face was the only reason we could tell she was older than 11. She was all curled up and her back was very deformed. She got polio when she was really young and she survived. Her parents couldn’t deal with a crippled child so they abandoned her to the orphanage. The nuns don’t have enough money to buy her a wheelchair or time to do physical therapy. We are using some of the money we collected from donations to get a wheelchair for her so she doesn’t have to ever drag herself around with only her arms again.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary3\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary3-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-2eb0e328-372f-7b9f-d3da-cb51a7367ade\">Though the traffic is CRAZY here, i think it is safe because everybody is watching out for themselves and looking more at their surroundings. In America there are so many rules that if somebody breaks one, people aren’t prepared and there is panic and confusion.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">People in India seem very casual and easy going. We were walking through the slums to get to the orphanage and we came across a few boys playing outside with a top. They said “hi” and I stopped to watch them and take their picture. They didn’t speak English but they all lined up for me to take a photo.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary4\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary4-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">It was surprising that people living in such poverty could be so free and friendly.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Even the dogs seem laid back; they never bark or chase you.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary5\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary5-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3730-d48f-f750-b23c8486e647\">The slums are very smelly and dirty. There are open sewers and piles of garbage throughout the slum village. The filth is scattered around houses and the marketplace.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And yet there is still beauty in the slums…</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary6.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary6\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary6-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary7\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary7-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3731-87c0-c81e-8d26bdc27188\">We have been visiting the Sahar slum orphanage that is run by sisters Eliza and Paulette of the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Today we went to the orphanage just expecting the thirty orphans but we found out that the orphanage is also the site of a low cost school for the slums. There were 500 kids aged 3-14 packed into classrooms with a collective space similar to a three bedroom apartment.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Some kids start school late so there are a few older kids in lower standards (grades). For example there is a girl in this slum school who was born and raised in a small village and her family just moved to the slum area to get jobs in the city. They then started sending her to the school so now she is in the second standard even though she’s already 13 years old.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary8\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary8-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary9\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary9-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Wednesday, December 16, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary10\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary10-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe were waiting outside the Sahar Orphanage and I was sketching out possible pictures for the kids to learn how to draw. A group of 4th standard slum kids just getting out of school walked by in their uniforms. They stopped to look at my pictures and my dad sat them all down around me and handed out sheets of paper. A boy and a small girl got their pencils out and I taught them how to draw a dinosaur. It was a happy experience changing this group of slum kid’s day from just average to great. They really like getting one on one attention and it feels really good to help these kids.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary11.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary11\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary11-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOn the same day we did a friendship bracelet project with the orphans. Some of the kids caught on really fast and didn’t need any help; they helped some of the younger kids who didn’t understand how to make the bracelets.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary12\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary12-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTalking with Sister Eliza, we learned more about the history of the orpahange. An old couple lived in a shack, in the Sahar Village slums, just behind the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. The husband worked pumping water from the nearby well. He was somehow murdered on the Flight Kitchen’s property and his body was thrown in a well. The Kitchen compensated the wife by giving her property on which she then built a small slum house. When she died she left the house and property to the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity. Eventually this property was expanded to become what is now the Sahar Village school and orphanage.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary13\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary13-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3734-8fa5-fcd9-014bbaa5d876\">Sister Eliza is about 50 years old but she looks like and has the energy of a much younger person. She came from Goa, India. When she was in college in Mumbai she studied Social Work in the slums and that is how she met Sister Paulette. Together they lived in the slums and were homeless until they were left a small home for their work.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sister Eliza is very lively but at the same time very strict with the orphans. All the kids respect her. She is always smiling and seems very happy about her work. She stays busy all day long. In the morning she teaches 4th standard at the orphanage/school. In the afternoon she goes and teaches at a private school to earn money for the orphanage. Every Saturday night she leaves for Vasai to join Sister Paulette for the weekend. Between teaching, traveling back and forth between her three orphanages, and running the orphanages, she’s left with no time to herself.</p>\r\nSister Paulette worked with Mother Teresa for about twenty years until she became very sick and was sent to a hospital in Mumbai. She was paralyzed and the doctor told her she was going to be bedridden for life. Sister Paulette told us that Mother Mary appeared to her and told her to get up and go back to help people. Somehow she had a miraculous recovery and started working in the Sahar Village Slum. Today she spends most of her time at the Vasai Orphanage helping the 200 kids there. Sister Paulette told us that she believes in “fighting poverty by education”. She says: “Giving food helps for a day or two but educating saves an entire life.”\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary14\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary14-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAma is the caretaker of the Sahar Orphanage, she monitors the kids and she is like their mother. She gave up her own home and all personal belongings to come and live at the orphanage. She bathes the kids and feeds them and dresses them. She is always there for them and most of the village knows her. Her being there takes a lot of the burden off Sister Eliza and frees her up to be able to go to the other orphanages. Ama can be very strict at times, and she really knows how to keep the kids in order. They are her whole life and she loves them like they are her own children.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary15\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary15-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe daily schedule for the Sahar Orphanage children starts in the morning with Ama bathing them and then feeding them. For breakfast they get one banana, one glass of milk, bread, butter, and jam. The bread, butter, and jam are donated by the Oberoi Flight Kitchen. Sister Eliza pays three Rupees for each kid to have an egg every morning. After breakfast they go to their classrooms until 1:00 p.m. Ama then feeds them a lunch of dhal, rice, and water. After they eat, they get rest and play time. A tutor comes in the afternoon and works with them. After this they get a snack and have free time until Ama is ready to feed them dinner. Dinner consists of a glass of water, rice, and leftovers from lunch and breakfast.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary16\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary16-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary17.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary17\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary17-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-6283-c35c-bd6907b38d00\">In Mumbai kids are usually orphaned because either the parents are in jail, they’ve died, or the fathers left the mothers. Often the story is that one or both of the parents have died of AIDS. In cases where the father has left the mother, the mother is often left homeless or unable to cope with a full time job and care for a child.</p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Once, we were walking home from a restaurant and we passed a frail middle aged woman holding a baby. She looked really sad. She was so desperate that she wasn’t begging for money, she was just standing in the middle of a street saying “khana” (food) to all passers. When we saw her, we gave her a bag of food that we got from the restaurant and she said: “God bless you.” Seeing people like that makes you want to give them everything you have because you know that they need it a lot more than you do.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary18\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary18-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-a7ee-8ff2-f70c3021eef4\">Poverty in India is EVERYWHERE. You could be inside the property of a five star, top line, hotel but as soon as you walk outside you would see a family bundled up on a few scraps of blankets. Or a mother trying to bathe her children in water from a pipe leak.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19.jpg\"><img alt=\"diary19\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary19-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3736-fb97-ecd7-dd6ff730c291\">In America poor people on the streets are usually not literally “on the streets.” There are soup kitchens and food lines they can go to, there are people who set up organizations to shelter the homeless for a night or two.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">And if a homeless person wanted to get off the streets, he/she probably could. In India, we did not see soup kitchens or “shelter for the poor” organizations; people are pretty much on their own. There are whole families living under a lean-to they’ve set up with scraps of blankets and wood. We saw a family</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-6910ac3f-3737-1e3a-f7ca-68ab726c3003\">bathing in water from a sewage leak right on a busy traffic road, and cooking in a tin can over a small fire. These families don’t have enough money to send their kids to school, and they’re too busy trying to get food to even think about education.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">[sectiontitle]Thursday, December 17, 2009[/sectiontitle]</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-92 alignnone\" alt=\"diary20\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary20-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1e-85b8-0f6e-6c08da776bc0\">At the Vasai Orphanage we saw that almost every kid had a skin infection on their legs and arms and other parts of the body. My dad sent pictures to an infection specialist at the University of Michigan and he wrote back with helpful advice to have one child with the infection tested at a local hospital.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Yesterday we took an orphan to Holy Spirit Hospital in Mumbai hoping to get some tests done. The hospitals in India are very different from American hospitals. There was a huge line of about forty people all waiting to get their papers and to get checked by just one doctor. When we finally got to see the doctor, he told us what we already thought- the orphan had scabies and bacteria infections of the skin. He did not allow any tests to be done.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">My dad became friends with a pharmacist nearby where we were staying. When the pharmacist heard what we were doing he said that he would give us medicine at the best price he could. We purchased enough medicine to treat all the orphans at both Vasai and Sahar.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-93\" alt=\"diary21\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary21-225x300.jpg\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1f-4aba-c7c3-ce380f6890fd\">We spent a lot of time making charts of which children should take what doses of each medicine. On the last day, my dad weighed all the kids at the Sahar orphanage to make it easier for Sister Eliza to distribute the medication.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary22.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-94\" alt=\"diary22\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary22-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be1f-b142-efc1-cebbe252de44\">At Vasai all the orphans and caretakers bathe with water from a very shallow well. The well is covered by a wire dome. Sister Eliza told us that the kids sometimes misbehaved and threw toothbrushes and spit in the well. Sometimes they even urinated in the well. The kids don\'t have parents to discipline them and Sisters Eliza and Paulette are doing the best they can. The well is also located a few feet away from the pit toilets and we are worried that when it rains there is cross-contamination.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">We talked to the Sisters about our concerns with the current water situation and they said that they were uncomfortable with it also. They have paid a man to go down and clean out the well and they put a solid cover over the well. They also built a locked fence around the well so no kids can get through.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this is a good short term solution to the water problem, in monsoon season, there is going to be a lot of cross contamination and the water will become filthy again. . They have been thinking about it for a while and they both thought that the best idea would be to get a solar powered water boiler installed. Getting and installing this boiler will cost 150,000 rupees (the equivalent of a little over 3,000 U.S. dollars). Our short term goal is to raise enough money to buy this boiler for the orphanage.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-2889-abfd-6562625193b9\">Today is our last day in Mumbai. We are taking a train to Vadodara to visit my dad\'s family. We are very glad to have had the chance to work at these orphanages.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">At times working at the orphanages was REALLY frustrating. The Orphans would start fighting for attention while we were talking to other kids and grabbing things from other kid’s hands. But at the end of every day at the orphanage, when they were all waving bye to us and walking us to the door shouting “good-bye Dee-Dee” (goodbye big sister) I felt good because I knew that the orphans were really happy. Seeing new people who wanted to help them was a big treat for them.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-95\" alt=\"diary23\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary23-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\" id=\"docs-internal-guid-4d8822e0-be20-7c6d-80ed-f258b5054a58\">I was glad that I wasn’t just out seeing the Taj-ma-hal or some other attraction; instead, I was finally doing something that helped someone else.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Writing this blog has been hard work because we are always doing it at the end of the day when we are exhausted and jet-lagged. I just want to go to sleep but my dad drags me down to the hotel lobby and asks to use the manager’s computer for a while. We go through all the pictures from the day, select the few we actually want to keep, and match them with things that had happened that day.</p>\r\nAfter volunteering only for one week I have become amazed that the Sisters have devoted their whole lives to doing this work. It’s REALLY HARD. They have given up everything in their lives to help the orphans and their whole lives revolve around them. The only reason they do ANYTHING is for the orphans. They are so self-less and devoted, and not many people are like them.\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-96\" alt=\"diary24\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary24-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Although this blog is for memories and for showing others how different lives are in the slums in India, it is also to raise money. The Sisters have a wish-list of things they can’t afford. The solar-water boiler for the Vasai orphanage is something we’ve seen that they really need and there is NO way that they are going to get this without donors. Our goal is to raise $3500 for this project. If you are reading this please consider making a donation.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary25.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-72\" alt=\"diary25\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/diary25-300x225.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div></div>','Diary of a Visit','','inherit','open','open','','9-revision-v1','','','2014-03-16 19:53:54','2014-03-16 19:53:54','',9,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/9-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(488,1,'2014-03-19 02:14:55','2014-03-19 02:14:55','&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"13\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-19 02:14:55','2014-03-19 02:14:55','',123,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(437,1,'2014-03-18 19:29:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2014-03-18 19:29:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://handmaids-local/?p=437',0,'post','',0),(443,1,'2014-03-18 20:20:06','2014-03-18 20:20:06','','DSCF7095 (Mobile)','','inherit','open','open','','dscf7095-mobile','','','2014-03-18 20:20:06','2014-03-18 20:20:06','',9,'http://handmaids-local/wp-content/uploads/DSCF7095-Mobile.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(414,1,'2014-03-15 17:33:29','2014-03-15 17:33:29','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\r\n\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"8\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 17:33:29','2014-03-15 17:33:29','',123,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(483,1,'2014-03-19 02:11:30','2014-03-19 02:11:30','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"13\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-19 02:11:30','2014-03-19 02:11:30','',123,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2014-03-15 17:33:52','2014-03-15 17:33:52','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\r\n\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"11\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 17:33:52','2014-03-15 17:33:52','',123,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(416,1,'2014-03-15 17:34:09','2014-03-15 17:34:09','Our Locations:  XXXX  Pictorial MAP GRAPHIC XXXX\r\n\r\nOur Postal Adresses:  XXX  Adresses of Church Pakadi,  Merces, Giriz  (within a box outline)  XXX\r\n\r\n[googlemap height=\"300\" zoom=\"13\" lat=\"19.0822507\" long=\"72.8812041\"]\r\n\r\nSend us an e-mail:\r\n\r\n[bestwebsoft_contact_form]','Contact Us','','inherit','open','open','','123-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 17:34:09','2014-03-15 17:34:09','',123,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/123-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(418,1,'2014-03-15 19:01:07','2014-03-15 19:01:07','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-257\" alt=\"DSC01043 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Sr Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 19:01:07','2014-03-15 19:01:07','',25,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(419,1,'2014-03-15 19:01:32','2014-03-15 19:01:32','<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-257\" alt=\"DSC01043 (Small)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01043-Small.jpg\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" /></a></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sr. Paulette comes from a Christian Indian family from the island of Mauritus.  In her youth she decided to become a nun and came to Calcutta to join Mother Teresa.  For about 20 years she worked with Mother Teresa mainly helping women and children and doing family planning work.  She developed a severe back condition which required hospitalization. She was sent to a Mumbai hospital where she spent several months.  When she emerged from recuperation Mother Teresa urged her to remain in Mumbai in a life of service.  This is how, in 1989,  she became the foundress of a new order of nuns called the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.  Today the order contains about 40 nuns;  about 10 of these are directly working with Sr. Paulette at the orphanages.</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Sr. Paulette','','inherit','open','open','','25-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 19:01:32','2014-03-15 19:01:32','',25,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/25-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(420,1,'2014-03-15 19:10:19','2014-03-15 19:10:19','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together they  worked and lived in the slum areas around the International Airport in Mumbai known as the Sahar Slums (the specific location of the current Sahar Orphanage is in the Church Pakadi slum).</span></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><a href=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-375 alignleft\" alt=\"DSC01136 (Custom)\" src=\"http://www.vitalypeker.com/handmaids/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/DSC01136-Custom.jpg\" width=\"320\" height=\"240\" /></a></p>\r\n Living and working in the slums they were aware of the serious problems faced by families, especially women and children: lack of food, severe malnutrition, lack of schooling or even a place to study, lack of electricity in their hut like living quarters, and even lack of a bathroom. The went door to door and did a lot of counseling, direct care, weighing of babies, tracking growth, giving food, taking of individuals to medical care, and gave other assistance.   Through their outreach the Srs. became known in the area and to local social service agencies.  Often,  orphaned children and babies would be left at their doorstep at Sahar and the Sisters would work diligently to care for them and place them into nearby orphanages.  Eventually it became very evident to them that they would have to run their own orphanage.\r\n\r\nIn the Sahar slum they got an opportunity to take care of a widowed lady in exchange for living at her meager home (a slum hut).  Upon her death she donated the property to the local church.  The sisters were able to purchase this property from the church to develop a home base.  Also  around that time they received a donation of land at Merces (a suburb of Mumbai) on which they built a convent house.  Both the Sahar and Merces sites began as convent houses for the HMBT order but grew to become orphanages around 1996, and the Sahar site grew to also become a school.   The HMBT order has relied entirely on donations and generating of funds from within.  There is no steady stream of funding coming from a parent organization.  In the early years the Srs. were helped greatly by donations from J.P. Morgan.  They were able to use this assistance to do the needed building construction.  Previously they were literally residing in huts or make shift domiciles without a roof.\r\n\r\nOver the years the sisters have overcome many challenges running their organization and being responsible for all the orphans under their care. Then, and even now, the sisters often arise at 5 in the morning and don’t retire till late at night attending to their mission diligently.  They have grown as an order from just 2 nuns to recently about 40 nuns.  About 10 of these are involved with the orphanages and the remainder are doing parish work in other states in India.\r\n\r\nThe orphanages  have evolved gradually into becoming girls only orphanages today.  The boys  previously living there have all been placed with other orphanages or extended family.  For practical reasons it was not possible to have co-ed orphanages.  The boys were often disruptive around girls, not having any male residential mentors or father figures.  Also,  it was not possible to maintain separate living quarters for boys and girls.    There is  some ongoing turnover of the resident children.  Some of the kids leave if extended family eventually claims them.  Some of the kids leave because they don’t tolerate the structure that is maintained at the orphanage.  Most, however, stay several years, all the way up to becoming young adults that get jobs and even marry and start their own families.\r\n\r\nIt has always been important to the Sisters to educate the children in their care.  They worked against many obstacles to develop a school at the Sahar Orphanage.   Over the years the school became more widely attended by even  non-orphan children from the adjacent and nearby slums.  Today this school goes through 7th standard and has 300 kids, all packed tightly in the orphanage house which is about 2000 square feet.  A typical classroom is about 200 square feet and holds about 30 kids.  The teachers, who come from nearby communities,  are paid 400 Rupees per month.  The children attending this school have no other viable school option.  They are unable to go to the already impacted government schools and nearby private schools are unaffordable for their families.  The HMBT school offers them a low cost education in subjects ranging from english, to science, to math, to crafts.  Were it not for this school, many of the kids would receive no education.  At Merces - Giriz the orphans all attend local independent schools, the cost of which is borne by the HMBT','History','','inherit','open','open','','141-revision-v1','','','2014-03-15 19:10:19','2014-03-15 19:10:19','',141,'http://handmaids-local/uncategorized/141-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(422,1,'2014-03-15 19:12:39','2014-03-15 19:12:39','<p dir=\"ltr\"><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">The Handmaids Orphanages were started by an order of nuns known as the Handmaids of the Blessed Trinity.   The main mission of the HMBT order was to reach out to impoverished women and children for their health and well being.  In the early years starting around 1989, and up to recently,  it was only Srs. Paulette and Eliza.  Together